==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|bakhows}}, {{m|enm|bakhous}}, {{m|enm|bachous}}, from {{inh|en|ang|bæchūs|t=bakery, bakehouse}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*bakahūs|t=bakehouse}}, equivalent to {{com|en|bake|house}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|bake-hous||bakehouse, bakery}}, {{cog|stq|Bakhuus||bakehouse}}, {{cog|fy|bakkhûs|t=bakehouse}}, {{cog|nl|bakhuis|t=bakehouse}}, {{cog|nds-de|Backhuus|t=bakehouse}}, {{cog|de|Backhaus|t=bakehouse, bakery}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈbeɪkhaʊs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A building or an apartment used for the preparing and baking of bread and other baked goods.
#* '''1548''', {{w|Hugh Latimer}}, ''A Notable Sermon of the Reverende Father Maister Hughe Latemer'', London,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A68325.0001.001]</sup>
#*: And they haue deuised for that purpose to make vs beleue in other vayne thynges by his pardonnes, as to haue remission of sinnes for praiynge on hallowed beades, for drinkyng of the '''bakehouse''' bole, as a Channon of Waltam Abbey, once tolde me, that when soeuer they putte theyr loaues of breade into the ouen, as manye as drancke of the pardon bolle shoulde haue pardon for drinckynge of it.
#* '''1793''', {{w|Charles Dibdin}}, ''The Younger Brother'', London: for the author, Volume 3, Chapter 5,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004892630.0001.003]</sup>
#*: This third scheme went to the relief of the poor at large, and indeed so did the fourth. One was a plan to sell them bread under the standard price, and the other meat. To carry the first into execution, a water-mill was built, and a '''bakehouse''' annexed to it.
#* '''1895''', {{w|Thomas Hardy}}, ''{{w|Jude the Obscure}}'', Chapter 2,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/153/153-h/153-h.htm]</sup>
#*: Jude, finding the general attention again centering on himself, went out to the '''bakehouse''', where he ate the cake provided for his breakfast.
#* '''2004''', {{w|Andrea Levy}}, ''{{w|Small Island (novel)|Small Island}}'', London: Review, Prologue, p. 3,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/smallisland00levy]</sup>
#*: Graham helped Father in the shed. He looked after the fire under the copper of pig swill, took the pork pies to the '''bakehouse''' when needed and generally ran round doing everything Father asked {{...}}
